16 "34-4-4.
17 (a) The Commissioner of Labor is authorized to grant exemptions to certain categories of
18 organizations and businesses for the purpose of exempting them from the operation of this
19 chapter. The exemptions so granted shall be based upon considerations of the value of
20 allowing certain classes of persons to be employed at rates below the minimum rate
21 because of overriding considerations of public policy to allow employment of certain
22 persons with disabilities and others who cannot otherwise compete effectively in the labor
23 market.
24 (b) The Commissioner of Labor is authorized to conduct investigations and compile
25 information as to the reasons for granting exemptions to certain organizations and
26 businesses pursuant to subsection (a) of this Code section. The Commissioner is required
27 to maintain a list of such exemptions, along with the records of the investigations
28 conducted and the basis for the granting of such exemptions, which list and records shall
29 be a public record. Reserved."
30 SECTION 3.
31 Said title is further amended in Code Section 34-6A-4, relating to prohibited discriminatory
32 activities, by adding a new subsection to read as follows:
33 "(a.1)(1) No employer shall utilize a certificate issued by the United States Department
34 of Labor pursuant to 29 U.S.C. Section 214(c) to pay individuals with disabilities who
35 are employed by such employer less than the minimum wage required to be paid by
36 employers to employees under federal law.
37 (2) Notwithstanding the provisions of subsection (a) of Code Section 34-4-3 and
38 paragraph (1) of this subsection, any employer that was issued a certificate by the United
39 States Department of Labor pursuant to 29 U.S.C. Section 214(c) on or before
40 July 1, 2025, may utilize such certificate to pay individuals with disabilities employed by
